courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand the mission, scope, goals, and functions of social work and social welfare;
2. comprehend the conceptions and roles of social welfare and social work in the changing society;
3. acquire knowledge on how social welfare and social work contribute to solving social problems and meeting needs under changing social conditions, with emphasis on the plights of vulnerable groups in the society;
4. gain an overview of the development, purpose, scope and content of social welfare services in Hong Kong;
5. understand social work as helping profession in social welfare, including its value and knowledge base, roles and functions, practice principles and methods; and

6. acquire foundation knowledge and essential values for the profession of social work.

Upon completion of course, the student will be able to:

1. Apply theories of social exclusion, marginalisation, social construction, and empowerment in understanding the situations and livelihoods of the socially disadvantaged groups in Hong Kong;

2. Review the structural causes and societal attitudes leading to social exclusion and marginalization of the socially disadvantaged groups;

3. Reflect on values and attitudes towards the socially disadvantaged groups critically;

4. Practice skills in planning and implementing community education project to empower the socially disadvantaged groups;

5. Identify community resources and practical methods in enhancing the well-being of the socially disadvantaged groups.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. Describe the common reactions and processes in dying and grieving;
2. Develop a developmental and contextual understanding on death, dying and bereavement;
3. Apply relevant knowledge to enhance adjustment to bereavement and live with grief; and
4. Reflect on their values, life priorities and meaning in life.

By the end of the course, students are expected to:

1. acquire basic understanding of major perspectives on human nature and development;

2. appreciate the interaction between individual and the social environment in the course of self development;

3. reflect on their current lifestyles and life goals, and contemplate on possible alternatives;

4. examine and reflect on significant issues in young adulthood.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. Critically review and discuss on different social and life issues which are relevant to themselves and others as human beings;
2. Apply social work perspectives and values in analysing different social phenomena and life issues through film media;
3. Develop their point of views towards different issues with critical mind; and
4. Show care and concern towards the well-being of people in need.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. acquire an understanding of the meaning of social work and the scope of its practice;
2. examine the philosophical base and core values of social work;
3. develop an understanding of the ethical and practice principles which guide social work practice; and
4. identify with the humanistic values of the social work profession, including social justice and promotion of the welfare of its clientele.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:

1. acquire knowledge, skills and attitudes related to inter-professional collaboration and practice in health care;
2. acquire knowledge in the health care promotion and disease treatment and prevention;
3. contextualize health care issues in the holistic and interprofessional context; and
4. identify and examine the significant roles and functions of social workers in health care system in Hong Kong.

After completing this online course, students will be able to:

1. Understand the concepts and value of S-L for the society and their personal development;
2. Apply the skills of communicating with various vulnerable communities;
3. Analyze the theories on assessing the needs of communities;
4. Apply the concepts of designing, planning, implementing and evaluating innovative service projects meeting the needs of the targeted communities; and
5. Reflect and integrate S-L with knowledge and skills acquired in their own disciplines.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. develop a perspective in understanding on human behavior in social environment;
2. acqure knowledge on the basic concepts, theoretical perspectives and issues in human growth and development;
3. outline human growth and behavior throughout the stages from pregnancy to late adulthood and the end of life with reference to socio-cultural contexts;
4. recognize the reciprocal relationships between human behavior and social environments throughout the life course;
5. apply knowledge on social work practice in relation to developmental needs, risk and protective factors; and
6. reflect on the values and attitudes toward human development.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. adopt a biopsychosocial perspective in conceptualizing mental health and mental disorders;
2. contextualize mental health problems and mental disorders in Hong Kong;
3. acquire knowledge in the holistic management of mental disorders;
4. acquire knowledge in the promotion of mental health and prevention of mental disorders; and
5. identify and examine the significant roles and functions of social workers in mental health services in Hong Kong.

Upon the completion of this course, students should be able to:

1. comprehend the meaning and nature of economic insecurity in globalized world;

2. understand the extent of economic insecurity and poverty in Hong Kong and in other societies;

3. acquire knowledge on social security as a societal measure to combat economic insecurity and poverty;

4. become familiar with the political and economic contexts in the development of social security, national differences in the provision of economic security, major types of provisions and issues of social security;

5. analyze contemporary debates regarding the philosophy and future direction of social security development in national and cross-national perspective.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:

1. Acquire knowledge of the key concepts and theoretical perspectives of multiculturalism, related social policies and service delivery system;

2. Apply an intercultural perspective to understand the struggles, challenges and socio-cultural barriers of ethnic groups in Hong Kong.

3. Evaluate the impact of culture on individuals and/or groups’ values, beliefs, behaviours, attitudes, preferences and life pursuits;

4. Develop awareness in cultural sensitivity and acquire cultural competence as well as intercultural intelligence

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to

· Understand how social entrepreneurs work to blend disparate goals, how and why social enterprises successfully fuse purpose and personal passion in business, and how visions and values are embedded in organizational culture;

· Be familiar with a variety of approaches and tools to measure organizational performance and social impact of social enterprise.

· Examine the key methods, strategies and models for social enterprises to succeed;

· Understand the dimensions and models of social entrepreneurship and the strategies on fundraising, financial management, opportunity seeking, social marketing, alliance building, etc.

· Apprehend how social enterprises leverage their work and impact to influence policy and the community;

Critically evaluate how social enterprise can fulfil the objectives of meeting economic, ecological and social needs.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to

· Realise how social innovations work to target social issues, creating social values through innovative strategies in various sectors as well as cross sectoral collaboration;

· Recognize the basic know-hows of social innovation such as design thinking, community or civic engagement, collaboration, prototyping and lean start-up;

· Apprehend how social innovation leverage their work and impact to catalyze changes in the broader community, economy or political sphere.

· Critically evaluate how social innovation can fulfil the objectives of coping with the challenges in the social, economic, cultural and political spheres.

· Acquire personal experience and prepare to taking own responsibilities as global citizen and ready to be social innovator / social entrepreneur in tackling the local, regional and global development challenges.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand the nature, principles and knowledge base of social casework;
2. develop a conceptual understanding of the psycho-social perspective in social work intervention;
3. examine social work values underpinning practice;
4. comprehend the core conditions of the helping process;
5. understand the diverse nature of social work roles and enhance the conscious use of self in the helping process;
6. master skills essential to casework intervention;
7. examine the current social casework practice in Hong Kong; and
8. increase sensitivity towards cultural and human diversity, and understand its importance in casework intervention.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand the nature, principles and knowledge base of social group work;
2. identify various stages of group development, and the roles of a social worker in respective stage;
3. understand the different conceptual models in social group work practice;
4. familiarize with group dynamics, and understand how they can be used to achieve the social work objectives;
5. appreciate the application of the group work method in working with different clientele groups; and
6. plan for a group and review group achieve.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand the nature, principles and knowledge base of community work: include the concept of empowerment and strength perspective.

2. identify various stages of community work intervention, and the roles of a social worker in respective stages;
3. understand the different conceptual models in community work practice, and apply these models in intervention planning;
4. familiarize with community dynamics, and understand how they can be used to achieve macro social work objectives;
5. appreciate the application of community work method in working with geographical and functional communities; and

6. plan a community work intervention and review its achievement.

It is hoped that through experiential encounters in laboratory drilling at the end of the course, the students are able to:

1. Reflect upon the helping attitude so as to achieve self understanding and personal growth;

2. Develop sensitivity in working with people;

3. Develop communication skills in working with individual, groups and communities;

4. Develop the ability to use social work knowledge to solve problems encountered in field practice; and

5. Reflect on social work values in field practice.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. gain an understanding of the theoretical framework and principles of some selected practice theories and approaches in working with individuals, families and groups;
2. acquire an ability to select and make use of practice theories to guide the assessment of the strengths, needs, problems and the social context of target clients;
3. develop an ability to systematically formulate intervention goals, treatment plans and intervention strategies in working with different types of client systems;
4. identify and examine ethical issues in current clinical social work practice, and

5. critically reflect on their own values and roles in the helping process.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. describe the nature and characteristics of welfare organizations, and articulate their implication to social welfare administration;
2. recognize the various management functions and tasks in welfare organizations;
3. recognize and understand the range of management and organizational theories relating to the management of welfare organizations;
4. apply management and organizational theories to analyze key issues and challenges in managing welfare organizations in Hong Kong; and
5. develop initiatives and change strategies to manage crisis and challenges confronting local welfare organizations.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. acquire basic knowledge of quantitative and qualitative social work research methods;
2. understand how social work research methods apply to social work practice and promote social justice;
3. conduct qualitative or/and quantitative research methods at undergraduate level; and

4. critically appraise current social work research studies.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. master the basic theoretical ideas, ethical considerations and practical context relevant to social policy in modern society;
2. understand the essential policies relevant to the general welfare of people, the vulnerable groups in particular;
3. examine key elements of decision making in policy fomulation and social service program development;
4. acquire basic skills of collecting, analysing and evaluating secondary data, including government official documents and statistics; and

5. critically evaluate policy literature in relation to the theoretical arguments.

Upon completion of this course, students are able to:

1. Demonstrate good knowledge and understanding of factors influencing the service development and social work practice in the placement agency and the service setting;
2. Identify with and apply social work values, assumptions and principles in practice;
3. Self-examine and reflect on learning and practice experience;
4. Make good use of social science knowledge in understanding and analysing human behaviour in social environment; and

5. Apply basic helping skills in different stages of social work interventions.

Upon completion of this course, students are able to:

1. Demonstrate good knowledge and understanding of factors influencing the service development and social work practice in the placement agency and the service setting;
2. Identify with and apply social work values, assumptions and principles in practice;
3. Self-examine and reflect on learning and practice experience;
4. Make good use of social science knowledge in understanding and analysing human behaviour in social environment; and

5. Apply basic helping skills in different stages of social work interventions.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. analyze the needs and characteristics of the clientele they served;

2. examine the interactions between the client system and factors at micro, meso, and macro levels;

3. apply social work theories or practice models to guide the formulation of intervention goals and strategies;

4. integrate the values, knowledge, and skills of social work practice; and

5. develop a positive attitude and stronger identification with the social work profession.

Upon completion of the courses, students would be able to:

(1) Understand the role of social work in contributing to the progress of local and global welfare systems;
(2) Apply social work concepts and theories independently in social work research;
(3) Master basic qualitative and quantitative research methods in social work;
(4) Develop awareness and understanding about policy and practice of social work in a global context.

Upon completion of the course, students are able to:

1. Understand human rights concepts and the international and regional human rights mechanisms;
2. Identify and understand major debates on equality and justice;
3. Critically analyze the impact of globalization on international and local policymaking;
4. Develop a sensitivity and resolution towards understanding conflicting rights situations under the influence of culture, politics, and economic;
5. Understand the interplay between international, regional and local actors in shaping the execution of policy; and

6. Explore the latest trends in international and social movements on global justice and policy advocacy.

The primary aim of the course is to provide students with value, knowledge and skills on employment and labour services round the globe in a comparative approach. By the end of the course, students should be able to:

1. Develop an understanding of the meaning and nature of labour and employment issues in Hong Kong and other contemporary societies;
2. Examine the extent of economic insecurity and unemployment in Hong Kong and in other societies e.g. China and UK;
3. Become familiar with the historical development, political and economic context, current provisions of labour and employment services in Hong Kong;
4. Study and review labour and employment services as a strategy in combat economic insecurity and unemployment;
5. Analyze current debate regarding the philosophy, strategy and future direction of labour and employment services in Hong Kong and in other countries.

### This course aims to equip the students with essential legal knowledge and professional attitudes so that they can **project** the risk, **protect** the vulnerable clients and **prevent** the tragedy and as far as possible with the necessary legal measures:

1. equipping themselves with knowledge about the legal and judicial systems of Hong Kong, an important structure to social work practice;
2. developing professional and fair attitude towards social advocacy and social responsibilities, which are the crucial professional attitudes and visions when helping the vulnerable people ;
3. acquiring knowledge and skills in statutory and legal requirements for risk assessment and risk management for effective and fair social work practice; and
4. contextualizing the dilemma in practicing law and contemporary philosophy and principles of social work.

Upon completion of this course, students are able to:

1. Work independently and manage work efficiently;
2. Take initiatives in learning, participation in agency activities and proposing ideas and plans;
3. Evaluate agency’s policies and practices and adopt multiple perspectives in analysis;
4. Study and analyze policies and broader issues having impact on clients and social services

5. Apply theories and practice approach appropriate to the target group and service context

6. Review practice experience and articulate principles for good practice

7. Apply skills to cope with more challenging tasks and difficult situations (e.g. engage related systems in intervention, alert to clients’ resistance and respond appropriately etc.)

