Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand what family-centered practice is;
2. acquire an eco-systemic-constructionist perspective in understanding and helping families and individual family members;
3. critically examine the relationship of the changing social context, family ideologies, policies on family and the needs of families in Hong Kong; and
4. apply the knowledge and principles of family-centered practice in needs assessment and service design.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand the needs and characteristics of young people in Hong Kong;
2. examine the historical development, objectives, and present operation of local youth services;
3. become familiar with the major youth social work approaches and practices in Hong Kong;
4. use social science theories to analyze current youth issues;
5. explore the life concerns and stories of young people and know how this exploration can help guide their intervention goals and actions; and
6. equip themselves with practical skills in empowering young people.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. acquire knowledge about the cultural, demographic, social, psychological, economic, and health status of the elderly in Hong Kong;
2. understand major sociological and psychological theories;
3. be equipped with social work professional values, ethics, and intervention methods with the elderly and their families; and
4. critically examine the adequacy of local elderly services and current policy issues for the elderly.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

a. understand the needs of people with special needs and their families, especially the psychosocial aspects, educational opportunities and legal aspects;
b. assess the roles of social workers in service provision, with special focus on inter-disciplinary cooperation among different professionals, case management and managed care;
c. critically appraise current services, legal and social context for people with special needs in Hong Kong; and

d. reflect the social construction and cultural perspective of disability.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. develop an understanding of meaning and nature of poverty and its relation to social exclusion in contemporary societies;
2. examine the issues of poverty and social exclusion in selected societies, i.e. Hong Kong, China and UK;
3. review different alleviation strategies in combat poverty and social exclusion;
4. understand the current provisions of poverty alleviation programs and anti-social exclusion strategies with reference to the political and economic context of Hong Kong;
5. critically evaluate different poverty alleviation and anti-social exclusion policies, approaches, program and projects in Hong Kong and other countries; and
6. examine the roles of social workers in organizing and implementing poverty alleviating and ending social exclusion projects.

Upon the completion of this course, students are expected to be able to

I. Knowledge:
a. Understand what is arts-based social work practice;
b. Acquire a Person-centered approach in using arts for empowerment.

II. Values:
a. Apply arts in accordance with social work values and code of ethics;
b. Demonstrate an ability to respect the boundaries of the helping relationship and other professionals/therapists.

III. Skills:
a. Provide a safe, supportive and non-judgmental environment to apply arts for empowerment;
b. Develop practical skills and sensitivity to apply arts in social work practice.

Upon successful completion of the course, students are expected to be able to:

1. Review and understand the position of women and people of various gender identities in local and global contexts;
2. Analyze gender power dynamics and oppression;
3. Examine current social policies and social work practices in addressing gender equality, oppression and discrimination;
4. Develop knowledge and skillsets on anti-oppressive, anti-racist practices.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. grasp the basic assumptions and theoretical foundation of family therapy;
2. acquire a systems perspective in family practice;
3. get hold of the values and principles of family practice;
4. familiarize with the major family therapy approaches;
5. equip with knowledge and skills in family assessment and family intervention;
6. develop ability in applying family therapy in different settings and with various target populations;
7. understand the importance of family research and evidence-based practice within a human context; and
8. integrate gender and cultural perspectives in family practice.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. utilize empirical methods to answer research questions;
2. implement different statistical and analytical methods, such as SPSS;
3. critically evaluate the effectiveness of particular research methods for different target groups;
4. analyze and apply research findings in social work practice;
4. 5. address values and ethical issues when implementing the scientific approach to social work practice; and

6. demonstrate understanding of ethical use of data and empirical information to address human problems.

Students who have completed this course are expected to have further understanding and mastery of:
1. basic assumptions, approaches, theoretical foundations and conceptual frameworks in family education;
2. professional skills in analyzing human behaviours and needs of participants in conducting family education;
3. critical thinking in reviewing and assessing family education programmes; and
4. using cultural perspective in development and evaluation of family education programmes.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
• Develop a holistic perspective to understand the social development and social welfare of contemporary China in a historical and global context;
• Recognize the historical, economic, social, cultural and political factors that shape the social welfare system of contemporary China;
• Become familiar with the pressing social issues in contemporary China, such as poverty, migration, healthcare, etc., as well as the policy responses to these social issues;
• Become familiar with the social welfare system of contemporary China and its underlying ideological and theoretical base;
• Develop the skills of critical thinking and analysis while evaluating the social welfare policies in China;
• Apply the knowledge and skills learnt from class to examine China’s social welfare policy in particular dimensions as well as to provide reasonable recommendations for policy change.

Upon completion of the course, it is expected that students would be able to:

a) identify significant intellectual trends in modern and postmodern social theories which have shaped the context for social welfare and social work practice;
b) comprehend the changing concepts and functions of social welfare, particularly amidst the rapid social, economic and political changes in the last few decades of the past century and in the new millennium;
c) reflect on the opportunities and challenges of social work in solving social problems and meeting needs under changing social conditions, with emphasis on the plight of vulnerable groups in society; and
d) recognize the relevance of knowledge on social theories to current issues and future development of social welfare and social work in Hong Kong.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to
• Realise how social innovations target social issues while creating social values through innovative strategies in social service sector;
• Recognize the basic know-how of social innovation and innovative practices such as design thinking, community or civic engagement, collaboration, prototyping and lean start-up;
• Apprehend how social intrapreneurs make use of innovative practice in social service agencies and NGOs;
• Understand how social innovations and innovative practices leverage social workers’ impact to catalyze changes in community, and the broader social, economic and political spheres.
• Critically evaluate how social innovations and innovative practices can fulfil the objectives, mission and values of social work profession.
• Develop personal competences and be prepared to be a social innovator / social intrapreneur/ social entrepreneur in workplace, community and global environment.

