Upon successful completion of this course, the students should be able to:
1. understand the meaning of help and develop more sensitivity and acceptance toward human nature and the uniqueness of individuals;
2. reflect on their basic attitudes in the helping process and have more capacity for self-awareness;
3. possess basic knowledge and communication skills in working with individuals and groups;
4. acquire skills in community need assessment;
5. examine and discuss direct practice issues in the context of local social service settings; and
6. appreciate the meaning of field instruction and make constructive use of it.

At the end of the course, students should be able to perform the following:
1. Apply organizational and management theories for analyzing specific organizational issues;
2. Critically assess management practices and issues in social service organizations;
3. Apply knowledge and techniques of scientific inquiry in developing social service management projects; and
4. Develop proposal for an evidence-based social service management study project.

