2. to apply theories, knowledge and skills in human resources in human service sector;
3. to reflect on students’ own leadership style and issues of team building in human service organizations;
4. to examine current issues and strategies of human resource management of social services in the local context and in the rest of China;
5. to integrate managerial theories and social work values in managing social service organization.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to
- Better understand how social ventures work to blend disparate goals, how and why social entrepreneurs successfully fuse purpose and personal passion in business, and how visions and values are embedded in organizational culture;
- Become familiar with the practices of social enterprises in different sectors, of various sizes, and with different visions;
- Better understand the key methods, strategies and models for social entrepreneurial organizations to succeed;
- Better understand how social enterprises leverage their work and impact to influence policy and systems change;
- Become familiar with a variety of approaches and tools to measure organizational performance and social impact of social entrepreneurial ventures.

At the end of the project, students should be able to:
- Identify a selected social problem or policy issue and delineate its significance;
- Formulate a topic with clear rationale/justifications related to the selected social problem or policy issue to capture critical concerns;
- Outline the linkage among research objectives, research questions, theoretical framework, and research methods learnt from other courses;
- Apply techniques of scientific inquiry to investigate the chosen topic; and
- Present the methodology, findings, discussion, and recommendations clearly and systematically in class presentation and in the dissertation.

Upon successful completion of this course, the student should:
1. Be able to identify and critically appraise research, designs and qualitative methods appropriate for the investigation of social problems or evaluating social policies;
2. Understand ethical issues in conducting qualitative social research;
3. Be able to develop and articulate the logic of different qualitative research methods and understand their strengths and weaknesses in doing social policy research;
4. Demonstrate at beginning competence in data collection methods and analysis such as observation and interviewing, secondary analysis and comparative approach;
5. Develop self-reflective and self-critical attitudes in conducting social policy research.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. Recognize significant ethical and legal issues concerning practice in marriage and family therapy;
2. Have enhanced sensitivity to legal and ethical issues in marriage and family therapy;
3. Do no harm to individuals and families when conducting marriage and family therapy;
4. Demonstrate competence to work with individuals, couples and families with diverse demographic and cultural backgrounds;
5. Respect and embrace human diversity; and
6. Have a self-reflection on personal and professional values and is able to adhere to professional values in practicing marriage and family therapy.

Upon the completion of the course, students will be able to:

- utilize systemic and contextual thinking in practice;
- apply the therapeutic and interpersonal skills essential to the success of the marriage and family therapy;
- administer different family assessment instruments appropriately and skillfully;
- work with family and larger systems effectively and collaboratively; and

- adhere to the ethical values and principles of family and couple work through a reflective practice.

