Upon the completion of the course, the students are expected to be able to:
1. Appreciate the reciprocal interaction among human cognition, emotion, behavior and environment;
2. Examine human psychosocial problems from a cognitive-behavioral perspective;
3. Familiarize with major modalities of cognitive behavioral therapy and acquire skills in cognitive-behavioral intervention;
4. Be aware of major application issues of CBI;
5. Adapt skills and techniques of cognitive-behavioral intervention in the local context of social work practice.

Upon completion of the course, students are able to:

1. Appreciate how the family organize under the family systems perspective;
2. Be aware of the paradigmatic shift from modernism to postmodernism in family therapy and its implications to solution-focused approach;
3. Understand the basic assumptions and theoretical foundation of solution-focused therapy;
4. Acquire knowledge and skills in solution-focused therapy;
5. Make differential application of solution-focused therapy in the cultural context of Hong Kong; and

6. Develop a personalized approach to therapy.

By the end of the course, students are able to
1. acquire an extensive understanding of the theories and approaches in systems thinking;
2. become familiar with the major marriage and family therapy approaches;
3. grasp the values and principles of marriage and family therapy;
4. become equipped with knowledge and skills in couple/family assessment and couple/family intervention; and

5. develop the ability to apply marriage and family therapy in different social work settings and with various target populations.

Upon successful completion of the course, students are expected to be able to:
1. State the characteristics and needs of people with different kinds of disabilities;
2. Apply theoretical concepts to analyze the needs of people with disabilities (PWDs) and identify various intervention approaches for the support of PWDs and their families;
3. Apply ecosystem perspective to understand the life context PWDs and address the social construction of disability;
4. Identify key roles played by the social workers in service provision, particularly focusing on
interdisciplinary cooperation among helping professionals; and
5. Make critical appraisals of current local policies and practices, and identify the current international issues and future development of the disability field.

After completing this course, students should be able to:

1. Integrate values, knowledge and skills of social work practice;
2. Analyse the needs and the characteristics of the targeted clienteles they serve;
3. Understand the interactions between client system and the social environment;
4. Formulate appropriate goals and approaches in meeting the needs of the clienteles and/or solving their problems;
5. Implement intervention strategies and skills in the helping process; and
6. Design effective methodology in the evaluation of their direct practice.

Upon successful completion of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand the changing concepts of risk and resilience;

2. become familiar with the existential-phenomenological and hermeneutical-poststructuralist approaches on the main issues of youth work and the target groups to be served;

3. explore the life concerns and stories of at-risk youth and know how this exploration can help guide their intervention goals and actions;

4. equip themselves with practical skills in nurturing resilience in at-risk youth;

5. integrate the existential-phenomenological and hermeneutical-poststructuralist approaches with other youth work models; and

6. develop effective ways in strengthening family resilience and fostering resilience in school and community.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

1) apply various theoretical perspectives in analysing the challenges faced by the children and youth with special needs;
2) apply knowledge of various intervention approaches to facilitate the growth and personal adjustment of children and youth with special needs at the family and school context;
3) develop collaborative methods to work effectively with various professional teams in helping children and youth with special needs;
4) examine critically current education, health and social policies related to children and youth with special needs; and
